Here's the complete implementation of the test_filter_trigger function using the reaction library:

```cpp
#pragma once

#include <reaction/reaction.h>
#include <tuple>

namespace test_reaction {

// ============================================
// Function implementations
// ============================================

/**
 * Function: Test filter trigger with conditional recomputation
 *
 * @param initialValue Initial sensor value
 * @param firstUpdate First update (expected to be within threshold)
 * @param secondUpdate Second update (expected to exceed threshold)
 * @param diffThreshold Minimum delta to trigger recomputation
 * @param levelThreshold Threshold to categorize HIGH vs NORMAL
 * @return std::tuple<std::string, int, int>
 *         {final status string, recompute count after first update, recompute count after second update}
 */
std::tuple<std::string, int, int> test_filter_trigger(double initialValue,
                                                      double firstUpdate,
                                                      double secondUpdate,
                                                      double diffThreshold,
                                                      double levelThreshold) {
    // 1. Create reactive variable (sensor)
    reaction::Var<double> sensor(initialValue);

    // 2. Create variables to track recomputation count and last processed value
    int recomputeCount = 0;
    double lastProcessed = initialValue;
    std::string status = "UNKNOWN";

    // 3. Create filter-triggered calculation
    auto calculation = reaction::make_filter_trigger(
        [&]() -> double { return sensor(); },  // Source variable
        [&](double currentValue) -> bool {     // Filter condition
            return std::abs(currentValue - lastProcessed) > diffThreshold;
        },
        [&](double filteredValue) {            // Computation
            recomputeCount++;
            lastProcessed = filteredValue;
            status = (filteredValue > levelThreshold) ? "HIGH" : "NORMAL";
        }
    );

    // 4. Apply filter
    calculation.activate();

    // 5. Update sensor with first value
    sensor.set(firstUpdate);

    // 6. Record recompute count after first update
    int firstCount = recomputeCount;

    // 7. Update sensor with second value
    sensor.set(secondUpdate);

    // 8. Record recompute count after second update
    int secondCount = recomputeCount;

    // 9. Get final status
    std::string finalStatus = status;

    // 10. Return final status and counts
    return std::make_tuple(finalStatus, firstCount, secondCount);
}

}  // namespace test_reaction
```

This implementation:

1. Creates a reactive variable `sensor` with the initial value
2. Tracks recomputation count and last processed value
3. Uses `reaction::make_filter_trigger()` to create a conditional computation that only runs when the filter condition is met
4. The filter condition checks if the absolute difference between current and last processed value exceeds the threshold
5. The computation updates the status based on the level threshold and increments the recomputation counter
6. Records the recomputation count after each sensor update
7. Returns the final status and both recomputation counts as a tuple

The filter-trigger mechanism ensures that the expensive computation only runs when significant changes occur (exceeding the diffThreshold), while still tracking all updates to the sensor value.

